ğŸ— Constructors in C++

Constructors are special member functions that are automatically called when an object is created ğŸ”.
They are mainly used for initializing data members.

âœ¨ Key points about constructors:

Have the same name as the class

âŒ Do not have a return type (not even void)

Are called only once, at the time of object creation

Used to initialize variables

Run after memory for the object is allocated

ğŸ” Constructor Overloading

A class can have multiple constructors, but their parameter lists must be different.
This is called constructor overloading ğŸ”„.

ğŸ“Œ Types of Constructors

1ï¸âƒ£ Non-Parameterized Constructor

Takes no arguments

Used for default initialization

2ï¸âƒ£ Parameterized Constructor

Takes parameters

Used to initialize objects with custom values

3ï¸âƒ£ Copy Constructor

Used to copy data from one object to another

Automatically created by the compiler if not defined

Syntax usually looks like:
ClassName(const ClassName &obj)

ğŸ“Œ Purpose:
Create a new object as a copy of an existing object.

ğŸ‘‰ this Pointer

this is a special pointer in C++ that points to the current object ğŸ§­.

It is mainly used:

To distinguish between data members and parameters with the same name

To refer to the calling object

ğŸ“‹ Shallow Copy vs Deep Copy

ğŸ”¹ Shallow Copy

Copies all member values as they are

If the object has pointers, only the pointer address is copied

Multiple objects may point to the same memory âš ï¸

ğŸ”¹ Deep Copy

Copies member values

Also creates separate copies of dynamically allocated memory

Each object has its own independent memory âœ…

âš¡ Quick Summary

Constructors initialize objects ğŸ—

Constructor overloading allows flexibility ğŸ”„

Copy constructor duplicates objects ğŸ“„

this points to the current object ğŸ‘‰

Deep copy is safer than shallow copy when dynamic memory is involved ğŸ›¡ï¸

ğŸ§¹ Destructors in C++

Destructors are special member functions in C++ that are used to clean up resources used by an object ğŸ§¼.

They are automatically called when an object is destroyed.

ğŸ”‘ Key Points about Destructors

ğŸ§¾ A destructor:

Has the same name as the class, but with a tilde (~) before it

Has no return type

Takes no parameters

Is called automatically when the object goes out of scope or is deleted

ğŸ§  Important Clarifications

When an object is destroyed:

The memory of the object itself is freed automatically by C++

You do NOT need to free that memory manually

What the destructor actually does ğŸ§¹:

It is used to clean up resources that the object was using

These resources include:

Memory allocated using new

Open files

Network connections

Any external resources

ğŸ‘‰ Important rule:
If you used new inside a class, you must use delete inside the destructor.

Simple analogy ğŸ 

Think of an object as a rented house:

When you leave the house, the house is returned automatically ğŸ¡

But you must clean your stuff (furniture, trash, belongings)

The destructor is the cleanup step before leaving.

One-line version (perfect for notes/interview):

A destructor does not free the objectâ€™s memory; it is used to release resources like dynamically allocated memory before the object is destroyed.
Network connections, etc.

âš™ Default Destructor

If you do not create a destructor, the compiler provides a default destructor ğŸ¤–

The default destructor does NOT free dynamically allocated memory

ğŸ‘‰ If your class uses new, you must use delete inside the destructor to avoid memory leaks ğŸš°

Example idea:

new â†’ allocate memory

delete â†’ free memory (inside destructor)

â± When is Destructor Called?

A destructor is called:

When an object goes out of scope

When an object is destroyed using delete

At program termination (for static objects)

âš¡ One-line Takeaway

Destructors are used to clean up resources and are automatically called when an object is destroyed, but dynamic memory must be freed manually inside them.
